Shadow Buffer
Motivation
  • Shadows are necessary for realistic scenes
  • We want to be able to have arbitrary geometry casting & receiving shadows
Question
  • What is a shadow?
  • Just a region where light doesn’t hit
  • I.e., the light source can’t “see” that area
Question
  • How can we determine where the light source cannot see?
  • One way: For each point that’s onscreen: Do a raycast
  • But: This is too slow!
Strategy
  • Create a map of everything that’s visible from light source’s point of view
  • Then when we render from camera, we just ask “Can the light see this location?”
Problem
  • Infinitely many points visible from light
  • But this approach is a good place to start…
Approach
  • Render scene from the light’s point of view to a shadow buffer
  • Record distance to each visible point in an FBO
Example
  • An example scene and the shadow buffer for it
  • Darker = closer, lighter = further away
Second Pass
  • After we have the shadow buffer, we’ll render the scene from the “real” camera
  • For each point the camera can see, we’ll ask “Is it visible in the shadow buffer?”
    • If yes, the point is lit
    • If no, the point is shadowed
Procedure
  • We need to tweak our camera a bit:
void Camera::setUniforms(){
    this->setUniforms("");
}
void Camera::setUniforms(std::string prefix){
    Program::setUniform(prefix+"viewMatrix",
        this->viewMatrix);
    Program::setUniform(prefix+"projMatrix",
        this->projMatrix);
    Program::setUniform(prefix+"eyePos", this->eye.xyz());
    Program::setUniform(prefix+"hither", this->hither);
    Program::setUniform(prefix+"yon", this->yon);
    Program::setUniform(prefix+"yonMinusHither",
        this->yon-this->hither);
}
Initialization
  • We create shadowbuffer like so: (In Globals):
    Framebuffer shadowBuffer{512,512,1,GL_R32F}
  • We also create a camera in Globals
    • Eye position = light’s position
    • Look direction = light’s direction
  • This is a floating point greyscale FBO
Explanation
  • Imagine we have a camera located where the light is, looking into scene
  • That’s the “light’s camera”
  • Just like any camera, we can compute a viewMatrix and projMatrix for it
  • Note: Our projection math requires camera fov to be ≤ 180°
  • In practice, anything over 90° starts to show unacceptable distortion
Render
  • Our render sequence will look like this:
void draw(){
    glClearColor(1,1,1,1);
    globs->lightManager.setUniforms();
    globs->shadowBuffer.setAsRenderTarget(true);
    globs->lightCamera.setUniforms();
    Program::setUniform("doingShadow",1.0f);
    drawObjects();
    globs->shadowBuffer.unsetAsRenderTarget();
    glClear(GL_COLOR_BUFFER_BIT | GL_DEPTH_BUFFER_BIT);
    Program::setUniform("doingShadow",0.0f);
    globs->shadowBuffer.texture->bind(5);
    globs->lightCamera.setUniforms("light_");
    globs->camera.setUniforms();
    drawObjects();
}
Question
  • Why 5 for the shadowbuffer texture?
    • 0=diffuse (base) texture
    • 1=emission texture
    • 2=metallic/roughness texture
    • 3=bumpmap texture
    • 4=environment map/skybox (cubemap)
    • 5=shadow buffer
    • 6=bone head/parent index texture (if we get to kinematics)
    • 7=bone animation texture (ditto)
    • 8=Perlin noise permutation texture (if using texture gradients)
    • 9=Perlin noise gradient texture (ditto)
    • 10=projective texture
    • 16=depth of field depth buffer (nearest sampling)
VS
  • VS needs to output a new variable: Eye space z value
FS
  • Fragment shader has a new texture input:
    • layout(binding=5) uniform sampler2DArray shadowBuffer;
  • And a new ‘in’ for the eye space Z
  • We need to have two code branches: One for doingShadow, one for not doingShadow
FS
  • If doingShadow is nonzero:
    • Let ez = -1 * eye space z
      • Because eye space z is negative
    • Compute: d = (ez-hither)/(yon-hither)
      • Observe: These are the light camera’s hither & yon
      • d will be 0 (eyespaceZ at hither) … 1 (at yon)
    • Set color = (d,d,d,1.0) and return
FS
  • If doingShadow is zero:
    • Let p = vec4(v_worldPos.xyz,1.0)
    • p = p * light_viewMatrix
      • Put p in light camera’s view space
    • distanceFromLight = -p.z
      • Get distance from camera (i.e., the light source)
    • p = p * light_projMatrix
      • Put p in light camera’s screen space
    • p.xy /= p.w; p.xy += vec2(1.0); p.xy *= 0.5;
      • Remap p.xy from -1…1 rightarrow 0…1:
Explanation
  • p is the 2D coordinate we need to sample from the shadowbuffer texture
  • The shadowbuffer itself contains distances from the light source
  • So: Pull the value out:
    • float t = texture( shadowBuffer, vec3( p.xy,0.0) ).r;
  • This value is in the range 0…1, so remap it:
    • shadowBufferDistance = light_hither + t * light_yonMinusHither;
Decision
  • Now we must decide if the light can see the world space point
  • When do we have shadow? If any of these are true:
    • distanceFromLight < light_hither
    • distanceFromLight > light_yon
    • distanceFromLight > shadowBufferDistance
Code
  • We can test for this without using or-conditions (might be more efficient):
bvec3 conditions = bvec3(
    distanceFromLight < light_hither,
    distanceFromLight > light_yon,
    distanceFromLight > shadowBufferDistance
);
if( any(conditions) ){
    not lit
} else {
    lit
}
Result
Why?
  • Float values have finite amount of precision
  • Reprojection may give slightly different results
  • Solution: Change our test a bit
  • Instead of
    distanceFromLight > shadowBufferDistance
  • Use:
    distanceFromLight > shadowBufferDistance + bias
Results
  • Bias of 0.001 (some artifacts) and 0.01 (no artifacts)
Or…
  • Another way: Omit the bias constant
  • Before rendering to shadow map, do
    glCullFace(GL_FRONT);
  • After rendering to shadow map (but before rendering main scene), do
    glCullFace(GL_BACK);
  • In setup:
    glEnable(GL_CULL_FACE);
  • Note: This won’t work if we want billboards to cast shadows (ex: particle systems)
Analysis
  • Our light’s FOV is pretty narrow…
  • Why don’t we get a “spotlight” effect where light can’t see scene?
Code
  • Need to add another condition to shadow test: If we would be sampling outside the texture, consider it to be in shadow
  • So these are our shadow conditions:
    • distanceFromLight < light_hither
    • distanceFromLight > light_yon
    • distanceFromLight > shadowBufferDistance + bias
    • any( lessThan(p.xy,vec2(0,0))) || any(greaterThan(p.xy,vec2(1.0,1.0)))
Analysis
  • Shadow buffers have some important advantages:
  • ANY geometry works.
    • If you can render it, it can cast and receive shadows!
    • Ex: Particle system (smoke) casts shadows
  • Arbitrary number of lights possible
  • But there are some problems…
Bias
  • Bias must be carefully tuned
    • If bias is too big: Shadows move away from objects (Peter Pan syndrome)
    • If too small: Shadow acne appears
  • Left: Correct image
  • Right: Too large bias → Shadow drifts away from sphere
Analysis
  • If shadow map resolution too small: We get aliasing (blocky shadows)
  • To get smoother map:
    • Increase size of FBO (More memory, more fill rate)
    • Make light FOV smaller (Lit region smaller)
  • Left: 512x512, 90°; Middle: 512x512, 40°; Right: 1024x1024, 90°
Analysis
  • We can have any number of lights, but each light requires a shadow buffer and a render pass
    • Too costly if many lights
    • Lights are limited to 90° fov
Assignment
  • Add shadow buffer shadows to your program
  • Pick a location for the light source
